>>----- Reply message -----
>>From: "Kirk T McDonald" <kirkmcd@Princeton.EDU>
>>To: "Antennex" <antenna-discussion@antennex.com>
>>Subject: [Antenna-discussion] crystal radios and the capture area =

>>paradox
>>Date: Fri, Oct 26, 2012 11:20
>>
>>
>>Folks,
>>
>>The role of "received power" by a radio antenna is obscured =

>by the use =

>>of an amplifier, which can in principle deliver any output power =

>>whatsoever, independent of the power intercepted from the =

>incident wave =

>>by the antenna.
>>
>>So, it may be interesting to return to considerations of early crystal
>>radios that involved no battery and no amplifier.   In these
>>devices the
>>signal power that one hears (in headphones) was derived from =

>the power =

>>in the incident wave.
>>
>>So, it is desirable that the crystal radio sets capture as much power =

>>from the incident wave as possible.
>>
>>The capture area theorem is that ANY small antenna that is MATCHED =

>>(TUNED) and LOSSLESS captures the same amount of power from the =

>>incident wave, namely the power in an area 3 lambda^2 / 4 pi of the =

>>incident wavefront.
>>
>>So, do we need to struggle to provide some special antenna =

>>configuration for crystal radios?
>>
>>And, why bother adding a ferrite to a loop antenna when the =

>ferrite is =

>>"lossy"?
>>
>>---------------------------------------------------------------
>>----------
>>Looking at ham web sites about crystal radios, there seem to be 2 =

>>classes of answers.
>>
>>Some sites say that one must use a big linear antenna, a
>>lambda/4 monopole
>>preferably.     Short of that, bigger is better (they say).
>>
>>Other sites say that you will do just fine with a small loop
>>antenna.   You
>>can add a ferrite if you want, but it is not necessary.
>>
>>---------------
>>I have my opinions as to the answers, but it would be interesting to =

>>hear from the List on this.
>>
>>--Kirk
>>
